  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_17081913" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/17081913" />
    <a title="Werner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/903390-werner"><img alt="Werner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1216337931p2/903390.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/17081913?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Werner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Werner" href="/user/show/903390-werner">Werner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Fans of serious historical fiction</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/903390-werner?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/903390-werner?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer17081913" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14202128669444145740">&quot;Some say that we shall never know and that to the gods we are like the flies that the boys kill on a summer day, and some say, on the contrary, that the very sparrows do not lose a feather that has not been brushed away by the finger of God.&quot;<br/><br/>Despite the exact date and time --Friday noon on July 20, 1714-- given in the opening sentence of this book, which for a long time gave me the impression that the author was dealing, albeit through fiction, with a real event, the titular bridge just outside</span>
  <span id="freeText14202128669444145740" style="display:none">"Some say that we shall never know and that to the gods we are like the flies that the boys kill on a summer day, and some say, on the contrary, that the very sparrows do not lose a feather that has not been brushed away by the finger of God."<br /><br />Despite the exact date and time --Friday noon on July 20, 1714-- given in the opening sentence of this book, which for a long time gave me the impression that the author was dealing, albeit through fiction, with a real event, the titular bridge just outside colonial Lima, Peru, the collapse of which killed the five people who happened to be on it, was actually a pure invention. (A couple of the characters are apparently historical, however). The premise simply provides an opportunity to explore the ancient central question of the book, the one which underlies the contrasting views set against each other in the quotation that opens this review: how can we reconcile the idea of a benevolent Providence, overseeing the world and the universe in a purposive fashion, with the fact of tragic events the purpose of which is not immediately discernible to human reason? To underscore this central concern, this is precisely the question Brother Juniper, a Franciscan who witnesses the accident, takes upon himself to definitively resolve, by researching the background of the persons who died in order to rationally demonstrate, once and for all, the Divine purpose behind the deaths in a way that will silence the skeptics.<br /><br />This is a short novel, with just 139 pages of text in the edition I read, apart from the front matter (with three of those pages almost blank between each of the five chapters, save for a Roman numeral and chapter title!), and it's a fairly quick read. It's not, however, a <i>light</i> read. A serious reader will be apt to pause several times in the course of a reading to consider what he/she has just read, and Wilder can pack a great deal of depth into a small page count. Narration is from an omniscient third person, in an often wry voice that nevertheless isn't without compassion. "Perhaps an Accident," the first chapter, sets the stage; then three chapters explore the lives of three of the victims, leading up to his/her fatal presence on the bridge. Finally, "Perhaps an Intention" deals with the aftermath of the disaster. Events are not always recounted in strictly linear fashion (at one point, for instance, we go back in time five years at a paragraph transition, and only the content signals the change), but surprisingly, this works well here. Characterizations are complex, full and very rounded; depiction of human nature is realistic, and colonial Peru in that era is brought to life convincingly (especially considering that the author had never been in South America). Wilder's prose is vivid and abounds in felicitous phrases, but it serves the story without being "artsy" for its own sake. The book deservedly won the Pulitzer Prize in 1928 on its merits.<br /><br />Wilder was not a Christian believer, in the New Testament sense; and he subsequently bemoaned the fact that the vast majority of readers of this book failed to pick up his intention to deny "the survival of identity after death." (Having read it this second time --I'd previously read it back in 1970 or thereabouts-- partly to specifically look for that, I can confidently say that we don't pick that up because it's not clearly expressed; the concluding six sentences, which are apparently the ones he was referring to, don't state that denial as such and can easily be understood in a very Christian fashion, especially since they're presented as the thoughts of an abbess!) However, he was most definitely a theist. While he doesn't state his conclusion explicitly, and doesn't provide an answer to the "problem of theodicy" any more than the book of Job does, various indications, such as the progression from the first to the last chapter titles, and the arc of one of the characters, suggests that he comes down on the side of the second group mentioned in my opening quote. (He does, though, take seriously the reality that humans can't rationally "prove" or define the intentions of God --the take-away here is that these have to be accepted on faith.) And his explicit insistence on the primacy and abiding significance of love is a very Christian message.<br /><br />(I read the book in the 1963 Time Reading Program Special Edition, which has an illuminating Introduction by Kay Boyle.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14202128669444145740" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

